{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=HNMS K-XVI.jpg |Ship caption=HNLMS ''K XVI'' in the [[Dutch East Indies]], circa 1939, shortly before the outbreak of [[World War II]]. }} {{Infobox ship career |Ship country=Netherlands |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Netherlands|navy}} |Ship name=HNLMS ''K XVI'' |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered=30 May 1929 |Ship awarded=31 May 1930 |Ship builder=[[Rotterdamsche Droogdok Maatschappij]] |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down=8 April 1933 |Ship launched= |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned=31 January 1934 |Ship identification= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honours= |Ship fate=Sunk on 25 December 1941 |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class={{Sclass-|K XIV|submarine}} |Ship displacement=*865&nbsp;tons surfaced *1045&nbsp;tons submerged |Ship length= {{convert|73.64|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|6.51|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} |Ship draught={{convert|3.93|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} |Ship power= |Ship propulsion=*2 × {{convert|1600|bhp|0|abbr=on}} [[diesel engine]]s *2 × {{convert|430|bhp|0|abbr=on}} [[electric motor]]s |Ship speed=*{{convert|17|kn|abbr=on|lk=in}} surfaced *{{convert|9|kn|abbr=on}} submerged |Ship range=*{{convert|10000|nmi|abbr=on|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|abbr=on}} on the surface *{{convert|26|nmi|abbr=on|lk=in}} at {{convert|8.5|kn|abbr=on}} submerged |Ship test depth= |Ship complement=38 |Ship armament=*4 × 21 inch bow [[torpedo tube]]s *2 × 21 inch stern torpedo tubes *2 × 21 inch external-traversing torpedo tubes forward of the conning tower *1 x 88 mm gun *2 x 40 mm guns |Ship notes= }} |}
'''HNLMS ''K XVI''''' was one of five {{Sclass-|K XIV|submarine}}s built for the [[Royal Netherlands Navy]] (RNN). Entering service in 1934, the submarine was deployed to the [[Netherlands East Indies]]. On 24 December 1941, ''K XVI'' torpedoed and sank the {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sagiri||2|up=yes}}; the first [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] submarine to sink a Japanese warship. A day later, the Dutch submarine was torpedoed by the [[Japanese submarine I-166|Japanese submarine ''I-66'']] (later renumbered to be I-166) off Borneo, with all aboard killed. The wreck of ''K XVI'' was rediscovered in October 2011 by a group of [[recreational diver]]s.
==Construction== ''K XVI'' was ordered from Rotterdam-based shipbuilder [[Rotterdamsche Droogdok Maatschappij]] on 30 May 1929, and was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 31 May 1930.<ref name=DutchSubs>{{cite web |url=http://www.dutchsubmarines.com/boats/boat_kxvi.htm |title=The submarine K XVI |work=DutchSubmarines.com |accessdate=28 October 2011}}</ref> The submarine was [[Ship launching|launched]] on 8 April 1933, and commissioned into the RNN on 31 January 1934.<ref name=DutchSubs/>
==Operational history== In January 1935, the boat was deployed to the [[Netherlands East Indies]].<ref name=DutchSubs/> She remained in this area after the start of World War II.<ref name=DutchSubs/>
On 24 December 1941, approximately {{convert|35|nmi|km}} off Kuching, the submarine torpedoed and sank the {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sagiri||2|up=yes}}.<ref name=OzAFP>Agence France-Presse, ''Missing Dutch WWII sub found off Borneo''</ref><ref name=DAlbas>D'Albas, ''Death of a Navy'', {{page needed|date=December 2011}}</ref><ref name=Brown>Brown, ''Warship Losses of World War II'', {{page needed|date=December 2011}}</ref> The destroyer's aft [[magazine (artillery)|magazine]] caught fire and exploded, sinking the ship with 121 of the 241 personnel aboard killed.<ref name=DAlbas/><ref name=Brown/> Later that evening, the submarine attempted to attack the destroyer {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Murakumo|1928|2}}, but was fended off by [[depth charge]]s.<ref name=DutchSubs/>
''K XVI'' was torpedoed by the {{ship|Japanese submarine|I-166||2|up=yes}} a day later, and sank with all 36 aboard.<ref name=DutchSubs/><ref name=OzAFP/> The boat was one of seven Dutch submarines lost during World War II.<ref name=OzAFP/>
On 25 October 2011, the Dutch [[Ministry of Defence (Netherlands)|Ministry of Defence]] announced that the wreck of ''K XVI'' had been found by Australian and Singaporean [[recreational diver]]s off the northern coast of Borneo.<ref name=OzAFP/>
