'''James Robert Laxer''' (22 December 1941&nbsp;– 23 February 2018), also known as '''Jim Laxer''', was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[political economist]], historian, [[public intellectual]], and political [[activism|activist]] who served as a professor at [[York University]].{{sfnm |1a1=Evans |1y=1991 |1p=306 |2a1=MacDonald |2a2=Gastmann |2y=2001 |2pp=292ff}}<ref name="neren">{{cite news |last=Nerenberg |first=Karl |author-link=Karl Nerenberg |date=26 February 2018 |title=James Laxer and the Movement He Helped Create |url=http://rabble.ca/news/2018/02/james-laxer-and-movement-he-helped-create |work=Rabble.ca |access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref> Best known as co-founder of [[the Waffle]], on whose behalf he ran for the [[New Democratic Party leadership election, 1971|leadership of the New Democratic Party in 1971]], he is the author of more than two dozen books, mostly on Canadian political economy and history.<ref>{{cite web |title=TPL Eh List: James Laxer |url=https://site.houseofanansi.com/event/tpl-eh-list-james-laxer/ |location=Toronto |publisher=House of Anansi Press |access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref>

==Early life and family==
Laxer was born in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], on 22 December 1941{{sfn|Laxer|2004|pp=7, 52}} and was the son of Edna May (née Quentin) and [[Robert Laxer]], a psychologist, professor, author, and political [[activism|activist]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fulford |first=Robert |author-link=Robert Fulford (journalist) |date=11 September 2004 |title=A Rare Glimpse at Canadian Stalinism |url=http://www.robertfulford.com/2004-09-11-laxer.html |newspaper=National Post |location=Toronto |access-date=23 February 2018}}</ref> His father was [[Jewish]] and his mother was from a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] family. Both were members of the [[Communist Party of Canada]] and its public face, the [[Labor-Progressive Party]], with Robert Laxer being a national organizer for the party. The Laxers left the party, along with many other members, following [[Khrushchev's Secret Speech]] revealing [[Joseph Stalin]]'s crimes, and the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|1956 Soviet invasion of Hungary]]. James Laxer wrote about his experiences growing up during this period in his memoir ''Red Diaper Baby: A Boyhood in the Age of McCarthyism''.{{sfn|Doughty|2005}} His father came to serve as a significant influence on his political worldview.{{sfn|Bullen|1983|p=192}}

His paternal grandfather was a [[rabbi]] and his maternal grandfather was a minister and [[Christian mission]]ary to [[China]], where Laxer's mother was born.{{sfn|Laxer|2004|p=54}} His brother, Gordon Laxer, would become a [[political economist]], author, and founder of the [[Parkland Institute]].<ref name=starobit>{{cite news |last=Rizza |first=Alanna |date=25 February 2018 |title=James Laxer, One-Time NDP Leadership Candidate, Dead at 76 |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2018/02/25/james-laxer-one-time-ndp-leadership-candidate-dead-at-76.html |work=Toronto Star |access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Gordon Laxer |url=http://www.parklandinstitute.ca/gordonlaxer |location=Edmonton |publisher=Parkland Institute |access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref>

He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of Toronto]] and [[Master of Arts]] (following approval of his thesis ''French-Canadian Newspapers and Imperial Defence, 1899–1914'' in 1967) and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degrees from [[Queen's University]].{{sfn|Laxer|1967}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Jim Laxer |url=http://people.laps.yorku.ca/people.nsf/researcherprofile?readform&shortname=jlaxer |location=Toronto |publisher=York University |access-date=23 February 2018}}</ref> He was an active student journalist both at ''[[The Varsity (newspaper)|The Varsity]]'' at the University of Toronto and later at the ''[[The Queen's Journal|Queen's Journal]]''<!--"The" wasn't part of the periodical's title during that period. --> and was elected president of [[Canadian University Press]] in 1965.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 January 1965 |title=Laxer Chosen CUP National President |url=https://archive.org/details/queensjournal92pt2 |newspaper=Queen's Journal |volume=92 |issue=23 |location=Kingston, Ontario |publisher=Alma Mater Society |access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref>

Laxer was thrice married. He married Diane Taylor in 1965, from whom he was divorced in 1969.<ref name="Harris family">{{cite web |last=Harris |first=James F. |year=2014 |title=James Robert Laxer |url=http://harris-history.com/tree/315.html |website=The Harris Family Historical Database |access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref>{{better source|date=February 2018}} He married Krista Mäeots<ref name="neren"/> in 1969 with whom he would have two children: [[Michael Laxer|Michael]] and Katherine (known as "Kate").<ref name="Harris family"/><ref name="globeobit">{{cite news|last1=Fitterman|first1=Lisa|title=James Laxer, 76, was one of the founders of the Waffle movement in the NDP|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/james-laxer-76-was-one-of-the-founders-of-the-waffle-movement-in-the-ndp/article38271189/|accessdate=March 12, 2018|work=Globe and Mail'|date=March 11, 2018}}</ref> They were [[marital separation|separated]] at the time of her death in 1978.<ref name="globeobit"/><ref>{{cite news |date=6 October 1978 |title=Producer's Death Halts Radio Show |newspaper=Ottawa Journal |p=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=3 November 1978 |title=Honeymoon Falls' Story Is One of Destruction |newspaper=Ottawa Journal |p=69}}</ref> Laxer married Sandra Price{{sfnm |1a1=Laxer |1y=2003 |2a1=Laxer |2y=2004 |2p=184}} in 1979 with whom he would have two more children: Emily and Jonathan.<ref name="Harris family"/><ref name="globeobit"/>

==Political career==
In 1969, Laxer, along with his father Robert Laxer, [[Mel Watkins]], and others, founded [[the Waffle]],{{sfn|Fleming|2010|p=182}} a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] group influenced by the [[New Left]], the anti–[[Vietnam War]] movement, and Canadian [[economic nationalism]], that tried to influence the direction of the [[New Democratic Party]] (NDP).{{sfnm |1a1=Azzi |1y=2012 |1p=223 |2a1=Pitsula |2y=2008 |2pp=39–40 |3a1=Watkins |3y=2015}} Laxer was a principal author of their [[Manifesto for an Independent Socialist Canada]] in 1969 alongside [[Ed Broadbent]] and [[Gerald Caplan]].{{sfn|McAllister|1984|p=108}} The manifesto was debated at the 1969 federal NDP convention and was rejected by the delegates in favour of a more moderate declaration.{{sfn|Pitsula|2008|p=40}}

In 1971, Laxer ran for the [[New Democratic Party leadership election, 1971|leadership]] of the federal NDP and shocked the convention by winning one-third of the vote on the fourth and final ballot against party stalwart [[David Lewis (politician)|David Lewis]].<ref name=starobit/>{{sfnm |1a1=Erickson |1a2=Laycock |1y=2015 |1p=16 |2a1=Isitt |2y=2011 |2p=187}} The Waffle was ultimately forced out of the NDP and briefly became a political party under the name Movement for an Independent Socialist Canada.<ref name=starobit/>{{sfn|Bullen|1983|p=212}} Laxer and other Wafflers unsuccessfully ran for [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]] in 1974.{{sfn|Laxer|1996|p=162}} This electoral failure led to the Waffle's demise,<ref name="Watkins">{{cite web |last=Watkins |first=Mel |author-link=Mel Watkins |date=27 February 2018 |title=Reflections on Jim Laxer |url=http://www.rabble.ca/blogs/bloggers/rabblecas-staff-blog/2018/02/mel-watkins-reflections-jim-laxer |work=Rabble.ca |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref> and Laxer concentrated on his work at [[York University]], where he was a professor of [[political science]] for 47 years,<ref name="globeobit"/> and in broadcasting.

In 1981, he was hired as director of research for the federal NDP, but left in controversy in 1983 when he published a report critiquing the party's economic policy as being "out of date".<ref>http://www.hansard.gov.yk.ca/25-legislature/003_March15_1984.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Laxer |first=Michael |author-link=Michael Laxer |date=26 February 2018 |title=Remembering James Laxer, Canadian Iconoclast |url=http://rabble.ca/blogs/bloggers/rabblecas-staff-blog/2018/02/remembering-james-laxer-canadian-iconoclast |website=Rabble.ca |access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref>

==Academic, writer, and broadcaster==
Laxer hosted ''The Real Story'', a nightly half-hour current affairs program on [[TVOntario]] in the early 1980s. He also variously wrote a column and [[op-ed]] pieces for the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' from the 1980s until shortly before his death, as well as op-ed pieces for ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''.<ref name=starobit/><ref>{{cite news |last=Laxer |first=James |date=9 September 2014 |title=Scottish Referendum: World's First Vote on Economic Inequality |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/scottish-referendum-the-worlds-first-vote-on-economic-inequality/article20489038/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref> He also played "Talleyrand", a mock political insider, on [[CBC Radio]]'s ''[[Morningside (radio program)|Morningside]]'' in the 1980s.<ref>http://archivesfa.library.yorku.ca/filelist/2003-009.166.pdf</ref>

Laxer co-wrote and presented the five-part [[National Film Board]] documentary series ''Reckoning: The Political Economy of Canada'' in 1986, which examined Canada's economic and political relationships with the United States<ref name=starobit/>{{sfn|Evans|1991|p=306}} and Canada's place in the changing global economy.<ref name=york/> Laxer and his co-writer won a [[Gemini Award]] in 1988 for Best Writing in an Information/Documentary  Program or Series for episode one of ''Reckoning'' titled "In Bed with an Elephant".<ref>{{cite news |date=January 1989 |title=Gemini Awards: The Winners |url=http://cinemacanada.athabascau.ca/index.php/cinema/article/download/4267/4301&ved=2ahUKEwioucv8hcjZAhVB4WMKHa7FAAUQFjARegQIABAB&usg=AOvVaw2_beB7nAEf42GoNr6nFT4g |work=Cinema Canada |access-date=28 February 2018}}{{dead link|date=February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=James Laxer|url=http://www.news.yorku.ca/experts/?name_or_keyword=Laxer&research_area=&submit=Search+the+Guide&search=Y|website=York University Experts Guide |location=Toronto |publisher=York University |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref> The [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] refused to air the series due to its critical view of [[free trade]] with the United States, which was being negotiated at the time, and it aired instead on [[TVOntario]] and other educational channels in Canada as well as a number of [[PBS]] stations in the [[United States]].{{sfn|Evans|1991|p=306}}<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Hays |first=Matthew |author-link=Matthew Hays |date=12 March 2009 |title=To NFB or Not to NFB |url=https://thewalrus.ca/2009-03-film/ |magazine=The Walrus |location=Toronto |access-date=23 February 2018}}</ref>

A [[democratic socialist]],<ref name=starobit/> Laxer believed that Canadian economic nationalism was a progressive force against the United States and [[American imperialism]].{{sfn|Burgess|2002|p=239}}<ref>{{cite web |date=26 February 2018 |title=Remembering Jim Laxer |url=http://ndpsocialists.ca/remembering-jim-laxer/ |publisher=NDP Socialist Caucus |access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref> He wrote extensively about the influence of American [[multinational corporation]]s in the Canadian economy, particularly in the oil and gas industry, and his agitation helped lead to the creation of [[Petro-Canada]].<ref name=york>{{cite web |year=2013 |orig-year=2002 |title=Inventory of the James Laxer Fonds |url=http://archivesfa.library.yorku.ca/fonds/ON00370-f0000166.htm |work=Clara Thomas Archives |location=Toronto |publisher=York University |access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref> The creation of the [[Foreign Investment Review Agency]], and the [[Canadian Development Corporation]] in the 1970s is also attributed in part to the work of Laxer, Watkins, and the Waffle.{{sfn|Smart|2009|p=316}} In the 1980s he strongly opposed the adoption of the [[Canada–US Free Trade Agreement]],{{sfn|Warnock|1988|p=320}} though he still believed that [[free trade agreement]]s were capable of being used to the advantage of the political left through the entrenchment of social charters.{{sfn|Mandel|1992|p=224}}

Laxer died suddenly and unexpectedly in [[Paris]] of heart-related problems on 23 February 2018 while in Europe researching a book on Canada's role in the [[Second World War]].<ref name="globeobit"/><ref name=starobit/><ref>{{cite web |last=Laxer |first=Michael |author-link=Michael Laxer |date=23 February 2018 |title=In Memoriam: James Laxer, 1941–2018 |url=http://theleftchapter.blogspot.ca/2018/02/in-memoriam-james-laxer-1941-2018.html |website=The Left Chapter |access-date=23 February 2018}}</ref>

